<subSubSection id="C309EEC62F70FFFB4EAFFF2BFAA2FEB0" pageId="10" pageNumber="161" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BACBD4D2F70FFFB4EAFFF2BFAA2FEB0" blockId="10.[151,1436,151,285]" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">
<emphasis id="B967615F2F70FFFB4EAFFF2BFDDEFF1C" bold="true" box="[199,513,151,176]" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Distribution and habitat.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C13C6CE2F70FFFB4C67FF2BFD1BFF1C" box="[527,708,151,176]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Bachia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="161" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pyburni">
<emphasis id="B967615F2F70FFFB4C67FF2BFD1BFF1C" box="[527,708,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Bachia pyburni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to northwestern 
<taxonomicName id="4C13C6CE2F70FFFB4A41FF2BFB40FF1C" box="[1065,1183,151,176]" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Meliolaceae" genus="Amazonia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Meliolales" pageId="10" pageNumber="195" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">Amazonia</taxonomicName>
, occurring in 
<collectingCountry id="F304FDDD2F70FFFB4B38FF2BFA48FF1C" box="[1360,1431,151,176]" name="Brazil" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F304FDDD2F70FFFB4EFFFF00FED2FF79" box="[151,269,188,213]" name="Venezuela" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry id="F304FDDD2F70FFFB4F20FF00FE66FF79" box="[328,441,188,213]" name="Colombia" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, where it is known from the Negro– 
<collectingRegion id="49D773AF2F70FFFB4D27FF00FC7EFF78" box="[847,929,188,212]" country="Colombia" name="Vaupes" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Vaupés</collectingRegion>
river systems and Neblina region (
<figureCitation id="1328A1C82F70FFFB4B43FF00FAB0FF78" box="[1323,1391,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1113,1135]" captionTargetBox="[154,1434,189,1086]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,179,1091]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Distribution of examined material of Amapasaurus tetradactylus, B. panoplia, B. peruana, B. pyburni, B. remota, B. scolecoides, and B. trisanale. Records of Bachia didactyla and B. scaea were obtained from the literature." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/581978/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). In 
<collectingCountry id="F304FDDD2F70FFFB4EFFFF63FF01FF54" box="[151,222,223,248]" name="Brazil" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, it occurs only in the state of 
<collectingRegion id="49D773AF2F70FFFB4C41FF5CFD7CFF54" box="[553,675,224,248]" country="Venezuela" name="Amazonas" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Amazonas</collectingRegion>
. 
<taxonomicName id="4C13C6CE2F70FFFB4CC5FF63FC84FF54" box="[685,859,223,248]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Bachia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="161" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pyburni">
<emphasis id="B967615F2F70FFFB4CC5FF63FC84FF54" box="[685,859,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Bachia pyburni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is fossorial and diurnal, inhabits both highland and lowland terra firme forests, where it is found in the soil and amid decaying roots (Kizirian &amp; McDiarmid 1998).
</paragraph>
